{{Infobox museum | name = Chemtou Museum | native_name = <big>'''متحف شمتو الاثري'''</big> | native_name_lang = | image = Entrée du musée archéologique de Chemtou.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Chemtou Museum entrance | alt = | map_type = | map_caption = | map_alt = | coordinates = | established = | location = [[Chemtou]], [[Tunisia]] | type = [[archaeological museum]] | collection = [[Numidia]]n items | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | publictransit = | car_park = | network = | website = {{Official|www.chimtou.com}} }} The '''Chemtou Museum''' is an [[archaeological museum]] located in [[Chemtou]], [[Tunisia]]. The [[museum]] was designed by archaeologists with the [[Tunisian National Heritage Institute]] and the [[German Archaeological Institute]] with offices located in [[Rome]], [[Italy]]. It has the distinction of being located in the area of the old [[Roman Empire|Roman]] city of Simmithu, near the entrepot's [[marble]] quarry in what was the ancient [[Berbers|Berber]] kingdom of [[Numidia]].
==Marble quarries== [[File:Funerary steles in Archaeological Museum of Chemtou.jpg|thumb|Funerary [[stele|stelae]] at the Chemtou Museum]] The exploitation of [[marble]] began on site in the 2nd century and was operated by the [[Roman emperor]]s. The location of the area, not far from the [[Medjerda River]], allowed for mass production for export.
The museum presents the archaeological discoveries made nearby. Among the remains exposed, include sandstone green schist (dated from the 3rd century BC). A [[tiara]] has also been excavated, which belonged to the Numidian royal family. In addition, there is the restored [[facade|façade]] of a religious monument on a hill nearby.
A series of Roman mill races to horizontal [[water turbine]]s have also been discovered. This indicates that [[Roman technology|technologically]], part of the activities at the site had been mechanised.
